Area: Copper River Basin
Description:
['Hidden Lake, which is dammed by the Kennicott Glacier, has begun to
release and may cause a significant rise on the Kennicott River at
McCarthy. The Kennicott River water level prior to the release
was 1342.5 ft, gage datum, on the river gage.', 'Expect water levels on the Kennicott River to rise an additional
2 to 5 feet over the next 24 to 48 hours.', 'This is a yearly event that occurs in mid to late summer. Due to the
lower than historical median water levels on the Kennicott River from
cooler temperatures this past week, the glacial dammed lake
release is expected to produce a smaller hydrographic response
than in previous years.', 'Persons living or traveling in the vicinity of the Kennicott
River are urged to prepare for rapidly rising water and possible
minor flooding and bank erosion during the next several days.
Persons traveling for recreation should avoid parking or camping
in low lying areas near the Kennicott River.', 'The Chitina and Copper Rivers will experience moderate rises in water
levels as the glacier dammed outburst wave progresses downstream.', 'EXPECTED IMPACTS: Minor river bank erosion. Possible minor
flooding in low lying areas.']

Area: Central Interior; Middle Tanana Valley; Deltana and Tanana Flats; Upper Tanana Valley and the Fortymile Country
Description:
['High water on the Tanana River into the Weekend', 'The Tanana River is running near bankfull at some locations
between Tok and Manley Hot Springs. This is the result of a
combination of heavy rain and recent warm weather causing
significant snowmelt and glacial runoff. Water levels on the
Tanana River are expected to gradually fall some over the next few
days, but additional rain moving into the central and eastern
Interior Friday night and Saturday will likely result in the river
remaining at an elevated level. Expect many gravel bars to remain
underwater into the weekend.']

Area: Maricopa, AZ
Description:
['The Arizona Department of Environmental Quality (ADEQ) has extended
an Ozone High Pollution Advisory for the Phoenix Metro Area through
Friday.', 'This means that forecast weather conditions combined with existing
ozone levels are expected to result in local maximum 8-hour ozone
concentrations that pose a health risk. Adverse health effects
increase as air quality deteriorates.', 'Ozone is an air contaminant which can cause breathing difficulties
for children, older adults, as well as persons with respiratory
problems. A decrease in physical activity is recommended.', 'You are urged to car pool, telecommute or use mass transit.
The use of gasoline-powered equipment should be reduced or done late
in the day.', 'For details on this High Pollution Advisory, visit the ADEQ internet
site at www.azdeq.gov/forecast/phoenix or call 602-771-2300.']

Area: San Francisco; North Bay Interior Valleys; San Francisco Bay Shoreline
Description:
['* WHAT...Minor coastal flooding expected at prone low lying
coastal locations across the San Francisco Bay shoreline during
peak high tide tonight.', '* WHERE...Low lying portions of the San Francisco Bayshore.
Localized impacts are also possible in low lying areas along
the Pacific shore as well.', '* WHEN...From 11 PM this evening to 4 AM PDT Saturday. Please
refer to local tidal data forecasts available for several
coastal and bayshore locations at www.tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov.', '* IMPACTS...Flooding of areas previously impacted by King Tide
events is expected, including low lying lots, parks, and roads
throughout the San Francisco Bay Shoreline with the highest high
tides. Difficulty navigating shallow bay waters during the
lowest low tides.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Tidal levels will also rise along the
Pacific coast but impacts will be more localized to areas along
the SF Bay shoreline. Tide poolers and beachgoers should be
familiar with the times and heights of local tidal levels to
avoid hazards that may arise from rapidly shifting water levels.']

Area: Modoc County Except for the Surprise Valley; Klamath Basin and the Fremont-Winema National Forest
Description:
['...FIRE WEATHER WATCH IN EFFECT FROM SUNDAY AFTERNOON THROUGH
SUNDAY EVENING FOR STRONG GUSTY WIND WITH LOW RH FOR FIRE WEATHER
ZONES 285 AND 624...', 'The National Weather Service in Medford has issued a Red Flag
Warning for Saturday afternoon and evening, and a Fire Weather
Watch for Sunday afternoon and evening...', '* Impacts:  Strong, gusty wind with low relative humidity and
critically dry vegetation will greatly increase the spread
potential of any new and existing fires.', '* Affected area:
In Northern CA Fire Zone....285. For the Red Flag Warning this includes
the communities of Alturas, Likely, and Tionesta. For the Fire
Weather Watch, this includes mainly the Warner Mountain range,
including Davis Creek and Willow Ranch.', 'In South Central OR Fire Zone....624. For the Red Flag Warning this
includes the communities of Lakeview and Valley Falls. The Fire
Weather Watch includes almost the same area.', '* Wind: West 10 to 20 mph with gusts up to 30 mph.', '* Humidity: As low as 8 percent.', '* Additional Details: For the Fire Weather Watch in CA-FWZ-285,
critically low humidities are expected over the whole zone,
including Alturas. Winds are not forecast to meet criteria except
in isolated areas across the central portion of the zone. If
winds trend stronger, the area of critical fire weather
conditions will need to be expanded.', '* View the hazard area in detail at:
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/mfr/HAZARD']

Area: Roan and Tavaputs Plateaus; Elkhead and Park Mountains; Central Colorado River Basin; Gore and Elk Mountains/Central Mountain Valleys; Flat Tops
Description:
['* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be
possible.', '* WHERE...Portions of northwest Colorado and west central Colorado,
including the following areas. In northwest Colorado, the Elkhead
and Park Mountains, Flat Tops and Roan and Tavaputs Plateaus. In
west central Colorado, the Central Colorado River Basin and the
Gore and Elk Mountains/Central Mountain Valleys.', '* WHEN...From 11 AM MDT this morning through 10 PM MDT this evening.', '* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers,
creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations. In
addition, heavy rainfall over the Grizzly Creek, Lake Christine
and Pine Gulch Fire burn areas, amongst others, is possible during
the period of the Watch. Residents and travellers near any of
these burn areas should prepare for potential flooding impacts. Be
sure to stay up to date with information from local authorities.
Heavy rainfall could trigger flash flooding of low-lying areas,
urbanized street flooding, and debris flows in and near recent
wildfire burn scars.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- An unusually potent surge of monsoon moisture is poised to
sweep over the region on Friday. This, combined with an upper
level disturbance moving over northwest Colorado during the
afternoon, raises the threat of excessive rainfall which may
lead to flash flooding and debris flows, particularly across
recent burn areas.']

impacts. Be sure to stay up to date with information from local
authorities. Heavy rainfall could trigger flash flooding of
low-lying areas, small streams and canyons, and debris flows.']

Area: Calhoun, FL; Jackson, FL
Description:
['The National Weather Service in Tallahassee has issued a', '* Flash Flood Warning for...
North Central Calhoun County in the panhandle of Florida...
Jackson County in the panhandle of Florida...', '* Until 800 AM CDT.', '* At 453 AM CDT, Doppler radar indicated thunderstorms producing
heavy rain across the warned area. Between 3 and 4 inches of rain
have fallen in the last 1 Hour. Flash flooding is ongoing or
expected to begin shortly.', 'HAZARD...Flash flooding caused by thunderstorms.', 'SOURCE...Radar.', 'IMPACT...Flash flooding of small creeks and streams, urban
areas, highways, streets and underpasses as well as
other poor drainage and low-lying areas.', '* Some locations that will experience flash flooding include...
Altha, Alliance, Sink Creek, Union City, Simsville, Henderson Mill
and Ocheesee.']

Area: Modoc County Except for the Surprise Valley; Klamath Basin and the Fremont-Winema National Forest
Description:
['...FIRE WEATHER WATCH IN EFFECT FROM SUNDAY AFTERNOON THROUGH
SUNDAY EVENING FOR STRONG GUSTY WIND WITH LOW RH FOR FIRE WEATHER
ZONES 285 AND 624...', 'The National Weather Service in Medford has issued a Red Flag
Warning for Saturday afternoon and evening, and a Fire Weather
Watch for Sunday afternoon and evening...', '* Impacts:  Strong, gusty wind with low relative humidity and
critically dry vegetation will greatly increase the spread
potential of any new and existing fires.', '* Affected area:
In Northern CA Fire Zone....285. For the Red Flag Warning this includes
the communities of Alturas, Likely, and Tionesta. For the Fire
Weather Watch, this includes mainly the Warner Mountain range,
including Davis Creek and Willow Ranch.', 'In South Central OR Fire Zone....624. For the Red Flag Warning this
includes the communities of Lakeview and Valley Falls. The Fire
Weather Watch includes almost the same area.', '* Wind: West 10 to 20 mph with gusts up to 30 mph.', '* Humidity: As low as 8 percent.', '* Additional Details: For the Fire Weather Watch in CA-FWZ-285,
critically low humidities are expected over the whole zone,
including Alturas. Winds are not forecast to meet criteria except
in isolated areas across the central portion of the zone. If
winds trend stronger, the area of critical fire weather
conditions will need to be expanded.', '* View the hazard area in detail at:
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/mfr/HAZARD']

Description:
['The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) has issued
an Ozone Action Day for the Dallas-Fort Worth area for Friday,
July 15, 2022.', 'Atmospheric conditions are expected to be favorable for producing
high levels of ozone air pollution in the Dallas-Fort Worth area
on Friday. You can help prevent ozone pollution by sharing a
ride, walking, riding a bicycle, taking your lunch to work,
avoiding drive-through lanes, conserving energy, and keeping your
vehicle properly tuned.', 'For more information on ozone:', 'Ozone: The Facts (www.tceq.texas.gov/goto/ozonefacts)', 'Air North Texas: (www.airnorthtexas.org)', 'EPA Air Now
(www.airnow.gov/index.cfm?action.local_state&STATEID=45&TAB=0)', 'Take care of Texas (www.takecareoftexas.org)', 'North Central Texas Council of Governments Air Quality

Area: Upper North Platte River Basin; Snowy Range; Laramie Valley
Description:
['* WHAT...Flash flooding and debris flows caused by excessive
rainfall continue to be possible over the Mullen Fire Burn Scar
Area.', '* WHERE...Portions of south central Wyoming and southeast Wyoming,
including the following areas, in south central Wyoming, Snowy
Range and Upper North Platte River Basin. In southeast Wyoming,
Laramie Valley.', '* WHEN...From 11 AM MDT this morning through this evening.', '* IMPACTS...Heavy rainfall, up to 1 inch in 30 to 45 minutes, is
possible during the period of the watch. Residents near the Mullen
Fire Burn Scar Area should prepare for potential flooding impacts.
Be sure to stay up to date with information from local
authorities. Heavy rainfall could trigger flash flooding of
low-lying areas, urbanized street flooding, and debris flows in
and near recent wildfire burn scars.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- National Weather Service Meteorologists are forecasting heavy
rainfall over the Mullen Fire Burn Scar Area, which may lead
to flash flooding and debris flows.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood']
